english:
  title: Preface to the Record of the Northern Campaign
  author: Lee Geuk-gam
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the autumn of the fourth year of Tianshun, the sovereign beheld how the Maoliangwei barbarians, ungrateful and treacherous, repeatedly violated our borders. Words alone could not move them to submission, so His Majesty commanded Minister of State Shin Suk-ju to lead our generals in punitive expedition. Where heaven's authority reached, none dared resist. The campaign succeeded without pitched battle. Upon return, the commanders presented their victories at the Great Temple, and rewards were distributed among officers and men. The sovereign then instructed Shin Suk-ju and myself, saying: "The barbarian multitude is utterly scattered, their tents now empty—no greater cause for celebration exists. Record the manner and sequence of this campaign in a chronicle for our descendants, that they forget not this martial achievement." Such is the sovereign's profound and far-reaching wisdom. When the record was completed and presented, I was commanded to compose this preface.

    I humbly consider: War and punishment are measures the sage employs only when necessity demands. We suppress the rebellious and reprove the fierce, administering justice according to their crimes—whether through great expeditions or small executions—all to safeguard our people and eliminate their torment. Our Great Founder rose from the northern frontier and united the eastern realm. Even before ascending the throne, the barbarian clans revered his authority and cherished his virtue, gathering to him without exception, serving faithfully in his campaigns and standing guard throughout his court. The Great King who followed preserved the legacy through enlightened governance that reached everywhere. The Sage King further brightened and enlarged this achievement, such that the lawless trembled and submitted without respite. Even fierce warlords like Mengko and Timur, and the Guan family—all shriveled and faded into ruin. Thus fortifications were established along the river down to the sea's mouth, standing magnificent and terrible, daring no man to transgress.

    When the Western Jurchen, Li Mancheol and others, grew proud and defiant, we sent generals to subdue them, sweeping their lairs clean. Neighboring strongholds collapsed and all tribes trembled. Our sovereign, having quelled internal strife and inherited the great throne, illuminated civilized culture and spread boundless grace. Even the frozen northern wastes submitted to our ordinance, their people yearning for imperial benevolence and offering tribute as loyal subjects. Even Li Mancheol reformed and surrendered in sincerity, sending his son as hostage.

    Yet the Eastern Jurchen chieftain Nangwel-ahan violated our laws and stirred conflict with our border commanders, bringing upon himself heaven's judgment. His followers, seduced by his schemes, delusionally imagined they too would be spared. Like serpents coiling and wasps gathering, they obstructed the sovereign's grace through their own folly. Taking advantage of every gap, they sparked fresh tumult. Still, the sovereign opened to them the path of reformation and extended again the grace of amnesty. But they knew not how to fear his majesty, nor how to be moved by his benevolence. Was not his righteous anger therefore just?

    Once the sovereign's strategy was set, swift as wind and rapid as thunder, in one decisive stroke he brought peace. Now all our multitudes dwell secure within the great commonwealth. Is this not the supreme valor of an emperor? At this time, as chief among the inner counselors, I attended the sovereign's deliberations. I witnessed how his divine wisdom pierces ten thousand leagues away, how his spiritual transformations manifest boundlessly. When he issued commands, each bore his own hand—not a hair's breadth from perfect. Like sun and moon illuminating all things, like heaven and earth creating all forms, his traces lie everywhere yet nowhere can be traced, his essence takes no shape yet in all shapes appears. His mighty deeds blaze forth beyond all measure. His imperial brush shines radiant through heaven and earth, shining down to endless ages. When sage sons and divine grandsons receive and read these words, they dare not be careless. In this way they shall match heaven's virtue and grasp the sublime spirit of divine might that slays without killing. The way of securing the people and controlling the barbarians extends no further than this.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Tianshun was the reign year of the Ming emperor; this refers to 1460 CE in Korea under King Sejo.
  - key: ''
    value: The Maoliangwei were Jurchen peoples from the northeastern frontier.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Great Temple' (태묘) refers to the royal ancestral shrine where military victories were formally reported.
  - key: ''
    value: Li Geuk-gam served as a high-ranking official and intimate advisor to the king during this period.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'divine might that slays without killing' invokes the Confucian ideal of governance through virtue rather than force alone.
